	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>New milk processing plant to be established in Uganda </h1>

			
			<h4>
												28 November 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to press reports, arrangements are in place to construct a milk powder processing plant to serve dairy farmers in the western region of Uganda, who have the capacity to supply 500,000 litres of milk daily. The plant ‘will reduce consumption of unprocessed milk’ in Uganda. The new plant, costing US$15 million, is expected to start operations in January 2012 with a capacity to produce skimmed-milk powder, butter oil, liquid milk, ghee and cheese.</p><p>The managing director of Midland Group has described the plant as ‘the most ultra modern powder milk plant in East Africa’, and phase 2 of the project includes setting up a unit to extract casein for export. The plant manager said the company ‘will not only create jobs for Ugandans but will also create competition in the raw milk sector and help farmers get right price for their produce’.</p><p>The Midland Group describes itself as ‘one of Uganda’s leading business conglomerates’, with a diversified range of business interests. According to the company website, the Midland Group grew out of Midland Emporium Ltd, which was formed in Kakamega, Kenya in 1937, with its involvement in the Ugandan market dating from 1994, when it was legally incorporated in Uganda. The Group has international trade experience through its flower business, which exports to the Netherlands.</p><p>This is the second milk powder plant established in Uganda, following the establishment of the first facility ‘a few years back’ by the Sameer Agriculture and Livestock Industries.</p><p>Currently ‘Uganda produces about 1.5 billion litres of milk per year with only 10% processed’. Over 80% of milk consumed in Uganda is consumed in raw form.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>The Monitor</i>, ‘New dairy plant to reduce unprocessed milk uptake’, 15 October 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201110150084.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201110150084.html</a></p><p><i>East African Business Week</i>, ‘Western Uganda gets new milk powder plant’, 17 October 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.busiweek.com/11/opportunities/1912-western-uganda-gets-new-milk-powder-plant" target="_self">http://www.busiweek.com/11/opportunities/1912-western-uganda-gets-new-mi...</a></p><p>Midland Group, ‘With a milk processing capacity of 200,000 litres per day, Midland’s dairy enterprise is geared up for success’, press release, undated</p><p>
<a href="http://www.midlandgroup.net/agro-business/pearl-dairy.html" target="_self">http://www.midlandgroup.net/agro-business/pearl-dairy.html</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Current investments in the EAC dairy sector need to be seen against the background of the new regional standards which, according to a World Bank report, establish microbiological levels that are currently ‘unreachable for nearly the entire EAC industry’. Without new investment this could carry serious trade consequences (see <i>Agritrade</i> article, ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/Initiatives-to-establish-an-EAC-regional-dairy-development-strategy" target="_blank">Initiatives to establish an EAC regional dairy development strategy</a>’, October 2011).</p><p>The issue of standards is critical in the dairy sector from a trade and public health perspective, with both COMESA and EAC taking a keen interest.</p><p>The EAC is in the process of developing, adopting and implementing a regional legal, regulatory and institutional framework for the EAC SPS Protocol. This has seen the establishment of the East African Dairy Regulatory Authorities Council to deal with regulatory constraints.&nbsp; The EAC has also set up the EAC Steering Committee on Trans-boundary Animal Diseases. However, there remain policy and infrastructural constraints that may make it challenging for these institutions to be effective in dealing with their mandates.</p><p>In COMESA, one of the issues that has remained unresolved is the intra-regional export of milk. For example, Zambia has refused the entry of milk from Kenya on quality grounds. While SPS concerns are real and need to be addressed, these can mutate into non-tariff barriers to trade that protect uncompetitive national producers.</p><p>Currently most consumers prefer raw milk, which is seen as cheaper and more wholesome. However, most public health authorities are concerned about food-safety risks associated with the consumption of raw milk, and are looking to increase consumption of processed milk on public health grounds. These health issues need to be addressed, alongside measures to:</p>
<ul>

<li>improve farm level productivity; </li>

<li>increase the efficiency of milk collection; </li>

<li>reduce wastage through investments in increased cold storage facilities. </li>

</ul>
<p>These elements require more investment in rural infrastructure to allow farmers to move milk to markets at lower cost, while enhancing the competitiveness of processors.</p><p>As elsewhere, issues related to the functioning of the dairy supply chain could well arise in Uganda and across the EAC. Close attention may need to be paid to milk pricing policy and the basis for the management of producer–processor relations. In this context, strengthening the capacity of national and regional dairy stakeholders and networks to engage in national and regional dairy sector policy formulation would appear to be important (including through the Eastern and Southern Africa Dairy Association, ESADA).&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
